  "body": "<!-- This form is for bug reports and feature requests ONLY! \r\n\r\nIf you're looking for help check [Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/kubernetes) and the [troubleshooting guide](https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug-application-cluster/troubleshooting/).\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**Is this a BUG REPORT or FEATURE REQUEST?**:\r\n\r\n/kind bug\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nThe DaemonSet controller will schedule a pod on a node when the old pod is still in Terminating state. This breaks the expectation that only one pod will be running at a time per node.\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\nThe DaemonSet controller should not let two pods running at the same time on the same node.\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\nCreate a DaemonSet. Set terminationGracePeriodSeconds to be relatively long. Kill a pod. Watch a new pod start on the same node when the old pod is still terminating.\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\nSeems this behavior was introduced in https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/43077\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`): 1.7.2\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration**: GKE\r\n- OS (e.g. from /etc/os-release):\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools:\r\n- Others:\r\n",
